Creating a TensorFlow CNN in C++ (Part 3: Freezing the Model and Augmenting it)

This is the third and final article about how to create a CNN over TensorFlow C++ API. In this article I’ll discuss implementing model freeze, save and load, and data augmentation

Background

The two previous articles (here and here) discussed how to implement a CNN, and then methods of train, validate and test it. Now you need to optimize the model to get better results and to deploy it to “Production” so you can do some predictions with the optimized model.

Just as in my previous articles, I’ll specify where TensorFlow is less mature in its C++ API and how to overcome these difficulties.

The code for this article is located here.

Freezing the model

Although freezing the model is the final step, I’ll discuss it first.

You build your model, and then you train and optimize it. Once you are happy with the results, you want to save the model weights and biases; change them from variables to constants.

When you do that, saving the model to disk will save the constants and later on when you load the model it is ready to run and can classify new images.

Old and new APIs

TensorFlow C++ API includes two sets of APIs:

– old ones (based on Session class); and

– new ones (based on ClientSession class)

I chose the new ones. However, I’ve noticed that some utility classes in the repository have not been migrates to the new API. The freeze/save utility class that comes with TensorFlow repository, uses the older API. It is implemented in the /tensorflow/cc/tools/freeze_saved_model.cc file and header.

To use the API, you should include the /tensorflow/cc/tools/freeze_saved_model.h file and call the FreezeSavedModel API call to freeze the model.

The problem is that you need to pass the session object (indirectly), so that the internal implementation can go into the live model to get the current values of the variables. However, you do not have a Session, you have a ClientSession, and this ClientSession does not expose its internal data that has this Session object.

So what do you do? There are a couple of strategies:

1. Reimplement the CNN using the old API, which means not only using Session, but also using strings as variable names instead of handles (the ‘auto’ declarations in the model creation code).

2. Bypass the need to send a Session object: collect the variable values before calling the API, and pass these values in addition to the other parameters.

I chose the second option. I wanted to keep the code clean so that someday, when someone ports this code to the new API, you can simply call it without the preparations.

How to freeze

In order to freeze the model, we need to find all the variables and their respective values.

The list of variables and biases is already available, we have it as a vector we used when creating the optimization graph (these are the variables we compute the gradients on).

So, all we need is a map object that maps between these variables and the current values:

vector<Tensor> out_tensors;//Extract: current weights and biases current valuesTF_CHECK_OK(t_session->Run(v_weights_biases , &out_tensors));unordered_map<string, Tensor> variable_to_value_map;int idx = 0;for(Output o: v_weights_biases){    variable_to_value_map[o.node()->name()] = out_tensors[idx];    idx++;}

Next we get the graph from the scope (like we did when we used TensorBoard for visualizing it).

Next we create a bundle. A bundle is a special structure that combines a session and a meta graph. The session will not be used (as explained earlier), since we already have the map we need.

The meta graph is a very complex class that is used for a variety of use cases, but we only need it for the SignatureDef use, which is similar to a function signature (inputs and outputs).

We fill it with the data and add also the graph itself:

SavedModelBundle saved_model_bundle;SignatureDef signature_def; (*signature_def.mutable_inputs()) [input_batch_var.name()].set_name(input_batch_var.name());(*signature_def.mutable_outputs())[out_classification.name()].set_name(out_classification.name());MetaGraphDef* meta_graph_def = &saved_model_bundle.meta_graph_def;(*meta_graph_def->mutable_signature_def())["signature_def"] = signature_def;*meta_graph_def->mutable_graph_def() = graph_def;SessionOptions session_options;saved_model_bundle.session.reset(NewSession(session_options));//even though we will not use it

Next we prepare a few more output params and call the modified API:

TF_CHECK_OK(FreezeSavedModel(saved_model_bundle, variable_to_value_map, &frozen_graph_def, &inputs, &outputs));

The parameter variable_to_value_map does not exist in the original API, I added it so we can skip the usage of the Session object. You can also look into the freeze_saved_model.cc file to see the other changes in the file to match that change.

Finally, we call WriteBinaryProto to save the frozen output graph to file.

Load a frozen model

Loading a model involves again the old API (meaning Session and not ClientSession):

std::unique_ptr<GraphDef> graph_def;SessionOptions options;f_session.reset(NewSession(options));graph_def.reset(new GraphDef());TF_CHECK_OK(ReadBinaryProto(Env::Default(), file_name, graph_def.get()));return f_session->Create(*graph_def.get());

We first create a Session, then create a GraphDef and finally read the protobuf file to create the graph in the session.

Running “production” model prediction

Due to the fact we use the old API to create the session, we also need a special method to run the model for prediction, using the same session we created earlier:

Status CatDogCNN::PredictFromFrozen(Tensor& image, int& result){    vector<Tensor> out_tensors;    Tensor t(DT_FLOAT, TensorShape({1}));    t.scalar<float>()(0) = 1.f;    //Inputs: image, drop rate 1 and skip drop.    TF_CHECK_OK(f_session->Run({{input_name, image}, {drop_rate_name, t}, {skip_drop_name, t}}, {out_name}, {}, &out_tensors));    auto mat = out_tensors[0].matrix<float>();    result = (mat(0, 0) > 0.5f)? 1 : 0;    return Status::OK();}

The method gets a single tensor image and returns the class (0 or 1: cat or dog).

Note how we use the names of the variables instead of the handles. Other than that, the rest of the code is self-explanatory.

Using the class methods in main

In main, I created an if branch which chooses whether we want to use a frozen model or train the model and later save it:

string proto_name = "/Users/bennyfriedman/Code/TF2example/TF2example/frozen/cnn.pb";bool use_frozen = false;if(!use_frozen){    … //this is where the model training code is    …    …//and at the end    s = model.FreezeSave(proto_name);    TF_CHECK_OK(s);}else //use the frozen model{    s = model.LoadSavedModel(proto_name);    TF_CHECK_OK(s);    //testing the model    s = model.CreateGraphForImage(false);//rebuild the image loading model without unstacking    TF_CHECK_OK(s);    string base_folder = "/Users/bennyfriedman/Code/TF2example/TF2example/data/cats_and_dogs_small/test";    vector<pair<Tensor, float>> all_files_tensors;    s = model.ReadFileTensors(base_folder, {make_pair("cats", 0), make_pair("dogs", 1)}, all_files_tensors);    TF_CHECK_OK(s);    //loop through the images and call PredictFromFrozen to get the prediction.}

Read the code in the repository to see how statistics are calculated.
Don’t forget you need to include the modified header file and add the modified cc file to your project so it will compile as part of the product.

Measuring model performance

We already saw how we calculate loss, accuracy and validation metrics.

Now the goal is to see a chart showing the change in the metric over time (progress with running the epochs). This will show us if we over fit or simply stop learning.

When using Keras API in Python, visualization of the metrics is built in.

In the C++ API you have two options:

1. Use the logging ops within the model to write the metrics to disk

2. Use the utility class Summary File Writer which we used to visualize the graph in a previous article, to save the metrics to disk outside the model

In both cases you visualize using TensorBoard.

Which one do you use? It depends. On one hand, inside the model is a bit easier since the API is a simple call to ScalarSummary operation. On the other hand, using the utility class gives you the flexibility of calculating the metrics outside the model.

I used the second option:

SummaryWriterInterface *w1;TF_CHECK_OK(CreateSummaryFileWriter(1, 0, "/Users/bennyfriedman/Code/TF2example/TF2example/graphs/loss/", "loss", Env::Default(), &w1));Tensor t(DT_FLOAT, TensorShape({1}));t.scalar<float>()(0) = loss_sum/num_batches;TF_CHECK_OK(w1->WriteScalar(epoch, t, "Original"));

First you create a Summary File Writer object, later you create a tensor with a shape of a scalar, and fill it with data using the accessor scalar<>().

Then you use WriteScalar to write it to disk.

The visualization will be done via TensorBoard (see below).

Combining charts

In most cases, you want to see how the metrics change over time in relation to each other. You want to see the charts one behind the other so you can compare accuracy to validation.

This is a bit confusing, so you need to pay attention:

1. For each metric you need a separate File Writer that saves data in a separate folder (the file name suffix parameter is less important)

2. For each version of the graph you need a unique tag (the string you pass to WriteScalar). Data with this tag will go in the same combined chart.

3. Consecutive runs of the program add different files on disk but TensorBoard will add the new data to the same charts unless you change the folder or erase the older files.

So the strategy should be:

1. Use 3 File Writer (one for each: loss, accuracy and validation metrics) with 3 sub-folders under the “/graphs” folder you should already have.

2. Use a different tag for each version of the model. E.g. I’m going to do some data augmentation which will increase the number of images that run through the model, so I’m going to use “Original” for the normal run and “Augmented” for the better model that has more data. This is for example the chart for “Original”:

As you can see, the loss is almost at 0 (0.0187) but there is a widening gap between accuracy and validation and also validation is not improving from about epoch 8. This means we are overfitting.

The only way to solve that is to get more data to train the model. Running more epochs cannot improve the model.

Data augmentation

One way of getting more data is to get more images. However, like in the Python Keras version of our model we can augment the images to “create” more data for training the model.

In Python this is very easy, you only specify what data augmentation you want to create, and everything is done for you behind the scenes.

With C++ API it is a bit more complex, but possible.

We need to create a new graph that will take the image batches and augment them.

I implemented 4 ways of augmenting data:

1. Flipping right to left (up and down does not make sense)

2. Rotating clockwise and counterclockwise up to a certain degree

3. Size the image up or down up to a certain factor

4. Shift horizontally or vertically up to a certain factor

In each way there is a random factor so we will create a variety of changes between the epochs. What you specify in main is the chances or limits:

float flip_ratio = 0.5f;float rotation_max_angles = 40.f;float scale_shift_factor = 0.2f;TF_CHECK_OK(model.CreateAugmentGraph(batch_size, image_side, flip_ratio, rotation_max_angles, scale_shift_factor));

The method CreateAugmentGraph creates the graph which later runs on each batch to create a different variation of the images in each epoch.

Flipping an image

Let’s first look at how we flip an image:

auto rand1 = RandomUniform(a_root, {batch_size}, DT_FLOAT);auto flips_vector = Floor(a_root, Add(a_root, rand1, flip_chances));auto flips_tensor = Cast(a_root, Reshape(a_root, flips_vector, {batch_size, 1, 1, 1}), DT_FLOAT);auto reverses = Reverse(a_root, input_images, {2}); // right to leftauto tensors_reversed = Mul(a_root, reverses, flips_tensor);auto tensors_normal = Mul(a_root, input_images, Sub(a_root, 1.f, flips_tensor));fliped_images = Add(a_root, tensors_reversed, tensors_normal);

First we create a random vector of the size of the batch. Then we add the flip chance factor and floor. This gives us a 1 or 0 for each image in the batch (flip or not).

Now we shape the vector, so it matches the shape of the image batch with 3 more dimensions.

Flipping is done by calling Reverse operation on the dimension 2 which is right to left.

Now we have two batches, one flipped and one normal. We call Multiply with the random vector and its complement to 1 on each of them to zero the images we do not need and add them together to get the augmented batch.

Doing projective transformations

Projective transformation is a mathematical way of transforming a tensor of any dimension into a new tensor while changing its “visual” properties through projection.

This is exactly what we need to shift or scale images as well as rotate them.

Fortunately, someone already implemented an operation for doing this transformation as part of the “Contrib” code that comes with TensorFlow repository.

The code is located in /tensorflow/contrib/image folder.

Unfortunately, the contributor did not fully implement the C++ API but did only the Python one. We can fix that.

Custom operation

TensorFlow is extensible. There are guides on how to add new operations so you can use them in your models. There are some Operations that have been developed by contributors, but did not get to be part of the core TensorFlow. They are in the Git repository, but will not compile as part of the basic package.

To be able to use them, we need to compile them separately (yes, using Bazel), add their binaries to the project and include a header file.

Controlling the code generation and compilation is the BUILD file used by Bazel.

When looking at the /tensorflow/contrib/image/BUILD file you can see a tf_gen_op_wrapper_py section which is in charge of generating a python wrapper on top of the operations but no tf_gen_op_wrapper_cc section which will create the wrapper for the C++ class. Also, a cc_library section is missing which will create the library that we want to link with.

Use the BUILD file from my repository to overwrite the original BUILD file and then run:

bazel build -c opt --verbose_failures //tensorflow/contrib/image:image_cc

When the build is over, you should have the library file /tensorflow/bazel-bin/tensorflow/contrib/image/libimage_cc.so which you can link with. Note that in case you copy it to your local workspace (under the project folder in lib sub-folder) you may need to use install_name_tool so that you will be able to eliminate the dyld errors.

Also generated by this build are the files /tensorflow/bazel-genfiles/tensorflow/contrib/image/image_ops.cc and header.

These are the wrapper classes that were generated from the contrib source files. We will need to include the header and add the cc file to our project.

Copy these two files together with the internal ops files generated in the same folder to your /include/tensorflow/contrib/image sub-folder under the project folder.

Now we are ready to use the custom operation (ImageProjectiveTransform)

Building the transforms data structure

ImageProjectiveTransform accepts, like other transformation operations, a parameter which is called transforms.

This is a tensor with 8 floats called a0, a1, a2, b0, b1, b2, c0, c1 and in case we deal with a batch of images, there is another dimension of the batch size (each images gets a set of 8 numbers).

To create this tensor, in our case shaped 20x8, we need to create an InputList (made from a vector) and concatenate it along axis 1. We cannot use Stack since this will result in a shape of 8x20 that will be rejected by the transformation operation.

To shift images horizontally or vertically (it is also called translate for some reason) we need to put the number of pixels in a2 and b2 (positive and negative numbers).

To scale the image (up size or down size) we need to put a factor (above or below 1) in a0 and b1.

Since we need to put a random factor as well, the calculation is done like this:

auto rand1 = RandomUniform(a_root, {batch_size, 1}, DT_FLOAT);auto rand2 = RandomUniform(a_root, {batch_size, 1}, DT_FLOAT);auto rand3 = RandomUniform(a_root, {batch_size, 1}, DT_FLOAT);auto rand4 = RandomUniform(a_root, {batch_size, 1}, DT_FLOAT);auto rand_shift1 = Sub(a_root, Mul(a_root, rand1, scale_shift_factor*2*image_side), scale_shift_factor*image_side);auto rand_shift2 = Sub(a_root, Mul(a_root, rand2, scale_shift_factor*2*image_side), scale_shift_factor*image_side);auto rand_scale1 = Add(a_root, Mul(a_root, rand3, scale_shift_factor*2), 1-scale_shift_factor);auto rand_scale2 = Add(a_root, Mul(a_root, rand4, scale_shift_factor*2), 1-scale_shift_factor);Input::Initializer zeros(0.f, {batch_size, 1});auto transforms = Concat(a_root, MakeTransforms(batch_size, rand_scale1, zeros, rand_shift1, zeros, rand_scale2, rand_shift2), Input::Initializer(1, {}));shifted_images = ImageProjectiveTransform(a_root, input_images, transforms, "BILINEAR");

First we create 4 random vectors (at the length of a batch). Since these are numbers between 0 and 1 we need to do some mathematical manipulation to get to the number we need. Note that the factors we pass into the calculation match the Keras API: when you pass 0.2, the scaling on each axis is between 0.8 to 1.2 and the shifting is up to 20% to the right or the left and up or down.

We zero the transformation members we do not use, and create the transforms by concatenation. MakeTransform is simply building the InputList.

Lastly we call the ImageProjectiveTransform with the image batch.

Rotating images

Rotation is a bit more complex, but it uses the same transformation structure and operation:

auto rand6 = RandomUniform(a_root, {batch_size}, DT_FLOAT);auto angles = Mul(a_root, Sub(a_root, rand6, 0.5f), max_angles*2);auto rand_angles = Div(a_root, Mul(a_root, angles, (float)M_PI), 180.f);auto sins = Sin(a_root, rand_angles);auto m_sins = Mul(a_root, sins, -1.f);auto coss = Cos(a_root, rand_angles);float img_side_1 = image_side - 1;auto x_offset = Div(a_root, Sub(a_root, img_side_1, Sub(a_root, Mul(a_root, coss, img_side_1), Mul(a_root, sins, img_side_1))), 2.f);auto y_offset = Div(a_root, Sub(a_root, img_side_1, Add(a_root, Mul(a_root, sins, img_side_1), Mul(a_root, coss, img_side_1))), 2.f);auto transforms = Concat(a_root, MakeTransforms(batch_size, coss, m_sins, x_offset, sins, coss, y_offset), Input::Initializer(1, {}));aug_tensor_output = ImageProjectiveTransform(a_root, fliped_images, transforms, "BILINEAR");

We first create a random vector, convert to positive or negative degrees, then to radians.

Next we calculate the sine, the minus sine, the cosine, etc.

Again we create a transforms and call the transformation operation. I implemented this method by looking at the python version of it (tf.contrib.image.rotate).

Review the complete code for creating the graph with all 4 transformations. There is some optimization in case you are not doing one or two of them.

Running the model on the input image batch is straightforward.

Validation of the augmented images

What if the images are transformed in such a way that they are no longer identifiable as a cat or a dog by the human eye? How do we check that?

I’ve written a utility method WriteBatchToImageFiles which helps you dump the augmented tensors back to image files you can view.

In the main loop of training (we do not augment the images in validation or test) you can see the following code:

if(augment_data){    //TF_CHECK_OK(model.WriteBatchToImageFiles(image_batches[b], "/Users/bennyfriedman/Code/TF2example/TF2example/data/cats_and_dogs_small", "source"));    Tensor augmented;    TF_CHECK_OK(model.RandomAugmentBatch(image_batches[b], augmented));    //TF_CHECK_OK(model.WriteBatchToImageFiles(augmented, "/Users/bennyfriedman/Code/TF2example/TF2example/data/cats_and_dogs_small", "augmented"));    s = model.TrainCNN(augmented, label_batches[b], results, loss);}else    s = model.TrainCNN(image_batches[b], label_batches[b], results, loss);

If we use augmented data (which we should), we first augment the batch and then call the TrainCNN method with the augmented tensors.

Uncomment the calls to WriteBatchToImageFiles before and after the augmentation to see how the images randomly change.

Model performance

Let’s see if the model performance has improved:

You can clearly see that even after 100 epochs the loss is still going down and the gap between the accuracy and the validation numbers is less significant.

It is still not perfect, we are well above 80% in the testing, but to improve that we should probably run more epochs and get fresh images.

Summary

In this series of articles (General, Part 1, Part 2), I showed how to use XCode for TensorFlow C++ development, how to create a CNN using the C++ API, visualize it, prepare data for it and optimize in a few ways. I tried to follow the steps of Arden Dertat in his fourth article and implement the same AlexNet he implemented in Keras Python.

I hope this will serve as a tutorial to others who start their way in TensorFlow while using C++ as the main language.

Let me know what you think. Suggestions are welcome!
